    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix memory corruption in DFT radix-3 decomposition indexing\n\n### Summary\nThe NR PHY DFT implementation contained a critical memory corruption bug in several radix-3 decomposition functions. The bug caused out-of-bounds memory accesses when processing large DFT sizes due to incorrect indexing of vectorized data buffers.\n\nThe issue occurred in functions dft1800, dft1944, and dft2160 where the loop iteration counts were incorrectly calculated, leading to accesses beyond the allocated simd_q15_t buffer boundaries. This resulted in sporadic segfaults and incorrect FFT outputs under certain channel conditions.\n\nThe root cause was a mismatch between the number of int16_t elements and simd_q15_t vector elements, where the code was using the int16_t count for simd_q15_t array indexing.\n\n### Changes\n- `openair1/PHY/TOOLS/oai_dfts.c`: Fixed indexing in dft1800, dft1944, and dft2160 functions\n- Corrected loop bounds from element count to vector count (divided by 8)\n- Updated buffer offset calculations to match vectorized addressing\n- Fixed scaling loop iterations to process correct number of vector elements\n\n### Reproduction\nThe issue can be reproduced by running NR downlink transmission with 1800-point DFT processing enabled under high traffic load. Symptoms include:\n- Segmentation faults in PHY processing threads\n- Incorrect channel estimation results\n- PDSCH decoding failures with high BLER\n- Memory sanitizer reports of out-of-bounds accesses in oai_dfts.c\n\nThe bug is most likely to manifest when all HARQ processes are active and the DFT functions are called at maximum rate.\n"
}